ide collection of writings—from religious texts to novels—Fenton sheds light on a rarely explored but important part of religious discourse in early America. As the Hebraic Indian theory evolved over the course of two centuries, it revealed how religious belief and national interest intersected in early American history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  aA Son of the Forest.  aA Star in the West.  aAncestry.  aAppendix.  aBeyond the Verge.  aChristianity.  aDNA.  aDe Witt Clinton Chipman.  aElias Boudinot.  aEliza Snow.  aElizabeth Warren.  aEsdras.  aEthan Smith.  aHenry Home, Lord Kames.  aHollow earth.  aIews in America.  aJames Adair.  aJames Fenimore Cooper.  aJews in America.  aJohn Eliot.  aJoseph Smith, Jr.  aManual Mordecai Noah.  aMethodism.  aMormonism.  aMound builders.  aNative Americans.  aNorth America.  aRace.  aRacial science.  aRoger Williams.  aThe Bee-Hunter.  aThe Book of Mormon.  aThe History of the American Indians.  aThomas Thorowgood.  aUnited States.  aWilliam Apess.  aarchaeology.  acitizenship.  acolonialism.  aethnography.  ahoney.  amonogenesis.  apolygenesis.  aprobability.  avanishing American.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479891726.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479891726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479891726